    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7d806e8b7ff3d12ef606bf322d72f78e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 182101,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 416564,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/416564/johan-sj%c3%b6berg",
                "reputation": 49392,
                "display_name": "Johan Sj&#246;berg",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 9,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1299258796,
            "creation_date": 1299258796,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>Can you force a java object into implementing an interface at runtime?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Yes, using <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/\">dynamic proxies<\/a> or byte-code rewriting. However, to me it seems like you're looking for the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adapter_pattern\"><code>Adapter pattern<\/code><\/a>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 5196980,
            "question_id": 5196941
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6d8ebb117e8d83d74ea95fbdd0f87e13?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 11683,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 22656,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/22656/jon-skeet",
                "reputation": 1521070,
                "display_name": "Jon Skeet",
                "accept_rate": 86
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1299258857,
            "creation_date": 1299258857,
            "body": "<p>You can't make the object itself implement the interface, but you could use something like <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/reflect/Proxy.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Proxy<\/a> to create an object which implements the interface and uses reflection to call the appropriate member on the original object.<\/p>\n\n<p>Of course, if it's just the one interface type and the one concrete type, you could easily write such a wrapper without using Proxy:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class BarWrapper implements Foo\n{\n    private final Bar bar;\n\n    public BarWrapper(Bar bar)\n    {\n        this.bar = bar;\n    }\n\n    public int someMethodInFoo()\n    {\n        return bar.someMethodInFoo();\n    }\n\n    // etc\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 5196991,
            "question_id": 5196941
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/gMMY3.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 96690,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 262683,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/262683/costi-ciudatu",
                "reputation": 38453,
                "display_name": "Costi Ciudatu"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1299259118,
            "creation_date": 1299259118,
            "body": "<p>This should be solvable with an adapter.\nHave an other class defined that implements your interface and delegates to the real object:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class YourAdapter implements YourInterface {\n\n    private final YourClass realObject;\n\n    public YourAdapter(YourClass realObject) {\n        this.realObject = realObject;\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public methodFromInterface() {\n        // you said the class has the same method signatures although it doesn't\n        // implement the interface, so this should work fine:\n        realObject.methodFromInterface();\n    }\n\n    // .......\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now, given a method that expects <code>YourInterface<\/code> and an object of type <code>YourClass<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>void someMethod(YourInterface param) {}\n\nvoid test() {\n    YourClass object = getFromSomewhere();\n    someMethod( YourAdapter(object) );\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 5197030,
            "question_id": 5196941
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/aLKQa.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 138128,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 342852,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/342852/sean-patrick-floyd",
                "reputation": 300632,
                "display_name": "Sean Patrick Floyd",
                "accept_rate": 97
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1299259279,
            "creation_date": 1299258910,
            "body": "<p>Basically there are two ways:<\/p>\n\n<p>a) write a decorator around your Object that implements the interface and delegates to your object (this can be done either by using proxies or by writing a simple adapter class)<\/p>\n\n<p>b) change the byte code. Spring AOP is not powerful enough to do that, but the AspectJ compiler is. It's a one-liner:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>declare parents: YourClass implements YourInterface;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Since you don't have access to the class source you will have to either use Load Time Weaving or weave the library jar. All of this is explained well in <a href=\"http://www.manning.com/laddad2/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">AspectJ in Action<\/a> by <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/485671/ramnivas\">Ramnivas Laddad<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 5196998,
            "question_id": 5196941,
            "last_edit_date": 1495541421
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/nhcvo.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 255665,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 535871,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/535871/ted-hopp",
                "reputation": 235290,
                "display_name": "Ted Hopp",
                "accept_rate": 84
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1299259185,
            "creation_date": 1299259185,
            "body": "<p>You can probably do what you want with <a href=\"http://www.jboss.org/javassist/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Javassist<\/a>, either by modifying the class's bytecode or creating a wrapper/proxy class.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 5197044,
            "question_id": 5196941
        }
